column28: For the following questions, we are interested in what you ideally desire in two long-term romantic partners (partner Blue and partner Orange) that you would have at the same time. Below are some of the many ways that romantic partners tend to be different from one another. You have 70 points to divide between these two ideal partners in whichever way you see fit. For each trait, you can award your ideal partners as few as zero points and as many as 10 points. When allocating these points, think about how much of a given trait you would like each ideal long-term partner to have. Remember: you are limited to a total of 70 points for both partners. This means that in order to add points to one quality, you must take points from another, and the more points you assign to one partner overall, the fewer will be available for the other. So be sure to only give points to the qualities that you truly want in each ideal partner. - Ambition (Partner Blue)

column70:
I was in an online relationship at one point, and they brought it up. I have read about it a lot before, I saw no issues against it. That relationship didn't last very long, but I never felt there was a reason against polyamory past that. I feel it is inherent human nature to desire a large familial belonging..it feels right to my soul and body, to give the respect to myself and the people around me the rights and freedoms that should be there.

About a decade has passed, and now it seems like monogamous people carry these negative traits that often border a much more toxic environment than what I desire. Like, a controlling and entitled nature, a more sexist and bigoted world. I do not know how much scientific truth is to that, but limiting my romantic relationships to experienced poly people has removed those things from my life.
